loop (prompt -> tokens one at a time)\n104:- [ ] WS7-06 Implement `Inference(prompt, max_tokens, temp, top_k, top_p);` HolyC API\n106:### WS8 — Integration & Polish\n107:- [ ] WS8-01 End-to-end test: load TinyLlama Q4_0, generate 50 tokens, compare quality\n108:- [ ] WS8-02 Memory usage profiling and optimization\n109:- [ ] WS8-03 Book of Truth integration hooks (log model load, each token, anomalies)\n110:- [ ] WS8-04 Interactive mode with streaming token output to TempleOS console\n111:- [ ] WS8-05 Performance tuning: identify and optimize top-5 hottest functions\n112:- [ ] WS8-06 Documentation: user guide for loading models and running inference\n114:### WS9 — GPU Compute Partition (IOMMU-Safe, Book-of-Truth-Audited)\n118:- [ ] WS9-01 GPU threat model: DMA risks, firmware opacity, MMIO attack surface, IOMMU bypass vectors\n119:- [ ] WS9-02 IOMMU (VT-d/AMD-Vi) initialization and enforcement — mandatory, no GPU without it\n120:- [ ] WS9-03 GPU memory partition design — dedicated physical region, never overlaps kernel/log pages\n121:- [ ] WS9-04 Explicit copy-in/copy-out protocol — CPU copies tensors to GPU region, triggers compute, copies results\n122:- [ ] WS9-05 PCIe device enumeration in HolyC — discover GPU via config space, map BARs\n123:- [ ] WS9-06 GPU command submission interface — minimal ring buffer, no proprietary driver\n124:- [ ] WS9-07 MMIO register map for target GPU compute dispatch (start with virtio-gpu or simple compute)\n125:- [ ] WS9-08 Book of Truth hooks: log every DMA mapping, every GPU command, every MMIO write\n126:- [ ] WS9-09 GPU compute shader/kernel format — simple dispatachable compute tasks\n127:- [ ] WS9-10 Matmul offload: move quantized matrix multiply to GPU, keep results in GPU partition\n128:- [ ] WS9-11 Attention score computation offload to GPU\n129:- [ ] WS9-12 GPU error handling: timeout, hang detection, forced reset, logged to Book of Truth\n130:- [ ] WS9-13 Benchmark: GPU vs CPU inference speed for TinyLlama 1.1B Q4_0\n131:- [ ] WS9-14 Fallback: if no IOMMU available, GPU disabled entirely — CPU-only mode, no exceptions\n133:### WS10 — Multi-Architecture Model Support\n134:- [ ] WS10-01 Abstract forward pass interface — model-agnostic layer dispatch\n135:- [ ] WS10-02 Mistral architecture support (sliding window attention, different GQA config)\n136:- [ ] WS10-03 Qwen2 architecture support (different FFN layout, tied embeddings)\n137:- [ ] WS10-04 Phi-3 architecture support (different attention pattern, block structure)\n138:- [ ] WS10-05 Architecture auto-detection from GGUF metadata keys\n139:- [ ] WS10-06 Model registry: map GGUF architecture string to forward pass implementation\n141:### WS11 — Extended Quantization Support\n142:- [ ] WS11-01 Q5_0 and Q5_1 quantization (5-bit, wider dynamic range)\n143:- [ ] WS11-02 Q2_K, Q3_K, Q4_K, Q5_K, Q6_K (k-quant family, mixed precision)\n144:- [ ] WS11-03 IQ quantization formats (importance-based, variable bit-width per weight)\n145:- [ ] WS11-04 Quantization format auto-selection from GGUF tensor type field\n146:- [ ] WS11-05 Performance comparison matrix: tok/s vs quantization level vs model size\n148:### WS12 — Model Conversion & Preparation Tooling (Host-Side)\n151:- [ ] WS12-01 GGUF model validator — verify file integrity, tensor checksums, format version\n152:- [ ] WS12-02 Model preparation guide: download from Hugging Face → quantize → copy to TempleOS disk\n153:- [ ] WS12-03 Ollama model extraction: pull Ollama blob → extract GGUF → validate\n154:- [ ] WS12-04 Model size calculator: predict RAM/disk requirements before loading\n155:- [ ] WS12-05 Reference output generator: run llama.cpp on known prompts, save expected outputs\n157:### WS14 — safetensors Format Support (Hugging Face Native)\n158:- [ ] WS14-01 Document safetensors binary format (header JSON + raw tensor data, no pickle)\n159:- [ ] WS14-02 Implement safetensors header parser in HolyC (JSON key-value, tensor offsets)\n160:- [ ] WS14-03 Implement safetensors tensor loa